<div id="review_4343828361" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4343828361" />
    <a title="Christian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111865610-christian"><img alt="Christian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1632159423p2/111865610.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4343828361?book_show_action=true">Nov 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christian" href="/user/show/111865610-christian">Christian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4343828361" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7476615844551614983">What a wonderful and bizarre adventure this was! The main character, quite the opposite of an unreliable narrator, was the only reliable thing in the book. His matter-of-fact explorations of his surrounds rang cynical and absurdist, and it was both darkly humorous and painfully reflective.<br/><br/>Really, I enjoyed this from every angle: the fish out of water story of a man befuddled by customs outside his time, the vastly creative technologies and societies of the future, and the conceptual chemical dep</span>
  <span id="freeText7476615844551614983" style="display:none">What a wonderful and bizarre adventure this was! The main character, quite the opposite of an unreliable narrator, was the only reliable thing in the book. His matter-of-fact explorations of his surrounds rang cynical and absurdist, and it was both darkly humorous and painfully reflective.<br /><br />Really, I enjoyed this from every angle: the fish out of water story of a man befuddled by customs outside his time, the vastly creative technologies and societies of the future, and the conceptual chemical dependencies that prop up a society "that could not endure itself." At times it felt like a cross between The Matrix and Huxley's Brave New World.<br /><br />Charming, distressing, and breathlessly funny from the first to the last page. This is dangerously close to becoming a new favorite of mine.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7476615844551614983" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


